        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2011-12-22 21:21:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 5.7/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/17bf6590-2ce2-11e1-ab2e-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "ef1ac7c4990404c8401f9ca500a2596f183684a6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-29 23:07:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nIt looks like the layout lock support on the MDS is only partly there. The connect data for the LDLM bit locks would report that LAYOUT is supported, but actually enqueueing the lock would fail, AFAICS.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "aeeb8d4579e61515a3ccb7a80b6ba5280c657334",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-03 09:35:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nCorrect, we anyway use a separate connect flag (which isn't set at connect time yet) to tell whether or not the layout lock is supported. This patch is mainly about adding #defines.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "29b1d480b0962db3d841c7707f2f501595c68d12",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-07 23:59:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI have no objection to landing the i_size_{read,write}() part of the patch, and #define MDS_INODELOCK_LAYOUT, but this goes beyond just defining constants.\n\nIt appears the clients will actually be getting MDS_INODELOCK_LAYOUT due to its inclusion in MDS_INODELOCK_FULL, but I don't know what effect that will have on the server thinking that the client will drop the layout if that lock is canceled.  If there is a good case for this (i.e. it will actually improve future interoperability, instead of (IMHO) possibly make it worse), it should be clearly explained in the commit comment what effect this part of the patch intends.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "d867d92b48a2267339bfdd77553ade9f4715b450",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-08 18:06:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)\n\nSure, i checked the impact of this change before submitting this patch and i have not discovered any problem with that given that client cannot acquire the layout lock anyway.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
